ctly affected by its destructive effects.Focusing primarily on lyrics that emerged in 1990s New York rap, which critiqued the music industry for being corrupt, unjust, and criminal, Bogazianos shows how many rappers began drawing parallels between the "rap game" and the "crack game." He argues that the symbolism of crack in rap's stance towards its own commercialization represents a moral debate that is far bigger than hip hop culture, highlighting the degree to which crack cocaine-although a drug long in decline-has come to represent the entire paradoxical predicament of punishment in the U.S. today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCrack (Drug)xUnited States. 0aCrack (Drug)zUnited States. 0aDrug controlxUnited States. 0aDrug controlzUnited States. 0aNarcotic lawsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aNarcotic lawszUnited States. 0aSentences (Criminal procedure)xUnited States. 0aSentences (Criminal procedure)zUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814787007.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814725160zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814725160/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA